28-year-old cook found dead in San Francisco shopping center
The 28-year-old cook, who recently moved to San Francisco, was found dead in a flight of stairs from a local mall this week.
However, the victim's brother says he can't imagine someone willing to hurt him, noting, "Things were finally going well for him."
"The body, found at Westfield Mall on Wednesday morning, has been identified as 28-year-old San Francisco resident Frank Galicia," the San Francisco Forensic Bureau said.
The San Francisco Police Department says the death has been classified as a homicide and the investigation is ongoing.
The victim's brother, Luis Galicia, told ABC's San Francisco-based broadcaster KGO that Frank, a former pickup line cook in Boston, got his dream job as a cook at San Francisco's Sons & Daughters restaurant six months ago.
A spokesperson for Sons & Daughters said they were "shocked and depressed" by his death.
"We are a small team that works as a close-knit family and will be greatly missed," the spokesperson said.
Our thoughts and condolences to Frank's family and friends during this difficult period.
Luis Galicia said Frank had stayed in hostels at first, but lately "Things have finally been going well for him."
"He found an apartment, he was dating a girl," Luis Galicia told KGO.
Luis Galicia said he couldn't imagine anyone willing to hurt his younger brother.
He had a kind soul and a big heart.
His way of communicating with the family was always to cook us a dish, to cook us dinner," said Luis Galicia.
He never wanted to be involved in any quarrel.
He was a brother who went with the flow.
"For all the bad things that are happening to this world, it was that uncut diamond that shone brightly every day," he said.
Anyone with information is asked to call the SFPD Hotline at 415-575-4444.
Churkin said that the meeting of the UN Security Council on Crimea was useful.
