Let's extend the fruiting.
What can be done to ensure that the harvest goes on until the end of the season?
Says Yulia Belopukhova, agronomist and summer resident.
It is time for tall tomatoes to arrange a haircut: remove new stepchildren, cut off the tops, remove all the leaves to the penultimate brush with fruits and inflorescences with small ovaries - will not have time to ripen.
All tomatoes, regardless of the "constitution", as well as peppers and eggplants, are fed with ash-superphosphate extract, treated with biological preparations (Mozmer - to accelerate the pouring and growth of fruits, Phytosporin-M, Phytolavin, Gamair, Bactofit - from diseases, Immunocytophyte - to increase immunity, Bitoxybacillin, Lepidocid, Phytoverm - if there are pests).
Of the chemicals in late summer, only copper sulfate, colloidal sulfur and green soap should be used.
We do the last watering of plants.
Long-wattled cucumbers in the greenhouse are lowered from the trellis so that the lower, bare part of the stem (25-40 cm) lies on the ground, water with warm water and Zircon solution, sprinkle the stem with 5-7 cm of compost.
It is also easy to prolong the fruiting of zucchini: cut off old leaves, pour warm water and a solution of complex fertilizer, pour fertile soil under the bush.
To protect against night cold, install arcs with covering material above the bed.
During the day, keep the plants open, and close them after sunset.
Signs of the end.
What indicates that Russia is emerging from the crisis?
Economists have seen signs of Russia emerging from its longest recession in twenty years.
According to analysts interviewed by Bloomberg, Russia's GDP shows a positive trend - in the second quarter, GDP fell by 0.8% in annual terms.
This figure is the lowest since the beginning of 2015.
According to the latest data from Rosstat, the decline of the Russian economy in the second quarter slowed to 0.6%.
The Central Bank and the Ministry of Economic Development have also recently announced the stabilization of the situation.
Slow growth is ahead.
According to CBR experts, the recession in the Russian economy is a thing of the past.
"The index assessment of Russian GDP suggests that the recession is left behind, and the slow growth of the economy is ahead," the Bank of Russia said in its bulletin "What trends say.
The regulator raised the modular estimate of GDP for the current quarter to 0.4%, the estimate for the fourth quarter is 0.5%.
According to the representative of the Ministry of Economic Development, during the second quarter, the decline in Russia's GDP stopped in the second quarter, amounting to 0.2%.
In the second quarter, the seasonally cleared decline in GDP was 0.2% compared to the previous quarter.
But during the quarter, the decline stopped: in April it was 0.2%, and in May and June the change in GDP was in the range of 0-0.15, "RIA Novosti quoted a representative of the Ministry of Economic Development as saying.
The slowdown in the decline of the Russian economy over the past five quarters indicates that "the bottom has been passed."
Among other markers indicating signs of revival of the national economy, Bloomberg calls the growth in demand for electricity and rail transportation, the revival of business.
If we make an adjustment for the fact that the year is a leap year, it is clear that the dynamics of plus 1% of electricity consumption can be half due to an additional working day.
Add to this the lower average annual temperature in the first quarter.
The next argument is the growth of freight traffic, but it is difficult to get accurate data here, and plus or minus 0.5% of the semi-annual volume can also be explained by seasonality," explains Kirill Yakovenko from ALOR BROKER.
However, there are other, more obvious signs of stabilization of the Russian economy.
For example, reducing price pressures.
In July, the consumer price index was 7.2% compared to 15.6% in the same month last year.
Moreover, over the past two weeks, Rosstat has recorded deflation.
Prices in Russia fell for the first time in five years.
If you look at the dynamics of the ruble exchange rate, which, although it showed strong fluctuations at the beginning of the year, has strengthened by 12% since the beginning of the year in August.
This is also one of the signs of recovery, which should be followed by indicators from the real sector of the economy," Yakovenko emphasizes.
In addition, since April in the Russian Federation there has been an increase in industrial production.
In June, the indicator rose by 1.7%.
The rate of decline in foreign trade turnover is slowing down from -32.8% in January 2016 to -20.7% in May.
Positive dynamics is also demonstrated by the situation on the labor market, where the unemployment rate fell to 5.4%.
It was lower only in September 2015 (5.2%).
Despite the prosperous situation in the labor market, the issue of real disposable incomes of the population leaves much to be desired.
In annual terms, the indicator is reduced by 4.8%.
This factor can hinder the economic recovery, since household spending makes a significant contribution to GDP.
As a rule, in the structure of the economy their share exceeds 50%.
In addition to low consumer activity, the Bank of Russia's tough policy can also be called a risk factor for economic growth.
The regulator keeps the rate at 10.5%, which does not have the best effect on the real sector.
A negative factor is also an insufficiently high level of investment, which hinders the development of industrial potential.
But in general, we can assume that by the end of the year the rate of decline of the Russian economy will slow down to -0.5% against -3.7% in 2015," says Irina Rogova, an analyst at Forex Club.
The process of naturalization of athletes, recently launched in Russian football and perfectly rooted in winter sports at the Sochi Olympics, is not yet so actively developed in summer sports.
If in the Olympic Games in Rio former foreigners perform for Russia, then in most cases we are talking about natives of countries - former republics of the Soviet Union.
But in Rio de Janeiro, we can observe the opposite process - a fairly large number of Russians perform under the flags of other states.
In each case, the history of the change of citizenship is different.
Someone's parents took to another country as a child, leaving no choice.
Someone could not stand the competition for a place in the Russian team.
And someone believed that better conditions for development in sports would be created abroad.
"AiF.ru" found at least 16 athletes who decided to change their Russian citizenship.
In the German passport of the 27-year-old girl it is written that her name is Lisa Red.
But earlier she was, of course, Elizabeth.
She was born in 1988 in Omsk.
Just four years later, as soon as the Soviet Union collapsed, Lisa's parents decided to emigrate to Germany.
The girl had no choice.
There she decided to follow in the footsteps of her older sister - to engage in athletics.
Like her sister, Lisa chose pole vaulting.
Had she stayed in Russia, it is unlikely that she would have been able to "move From the throne" Yelena Isinbayeva.
Unfortunately, at the Olympics in Rio, Lisa will be our only countrywoman, albeit a former one, in the sector for pole vaulting.
Her best achievements in this sport are the bronze medal of the 2010 European Championships and the silver of the Continental Championships in 2016, which she won again in the absence of Yelena Isinbayeva.
29-year-old Elena Pirozhkova was born in Novokuznetsk in 1986.
Her parents are religious propagandists of the evangelical direction.
Largely because of their faith, they left for the United States when the girl was only three years old.
In addition to Elena, eight more children grew up in the family.
They all lived in the small town of Greenfield, Massachusetts.
Lena began to be fond of wrestling at school.
Showing good results, she moved to the city of Colorado Springs, where she continued her studies at the US Wrestling Training Center under the guidance of another former Russian Vladislav Izboynikov.
At the 2012 Olympics in London, Elena lost in her first fight.
But at the World Cup in the same year - a victory.
Before that, by the way, she managed to win silver at the 2010 World Championships.
After that, there was bronze in 2013 and silver in 2014.
26-year-old Maria was born in the city of Yaroslavl, where she first got acquainted with synchronized swimming.
But to say that she was brought up by our coaches in Russia would be wrong.
Soon the girl's family decided to emigrate to the United States and settle in the city of Colorado.
There Maria continued her studies.
Soon she was already a member of the US team and showed excellent results at the Pan American Games.
It is clear that at a serious international level, it cannot compete with Russian synchronized swimmers, but for America its indicators are a ceiling.
Kristina Shaldybina received a new name, which in Russian sounds strange, at the age of 11, when her parents decided to continue teaching the girl rhythmic gymnastics overseas.
Up to this point, the girl was engaged in her favorite sport in her native Yaroslavl.
After emigrating to the United States, she quickly entered the youth team of this country, and later broke into the main national team.
At the Pan American Games, 19-year-old Kristen won gold and silver.
For the first positions on the world stage, she, of course, did not have to fight, but for the United States she organized a real breakthrough - she led the stars and stripes team to the Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro.
Another of our former "artists" is Jana Berezko-Marglander, who plays for the German national team.
Yana was born in Togliatti.
In 2008, when the girl was 13 years old, the family decided to move to Germany - there the girl had more prospects to get into the national team.
Soon she was already representing her country at the 2012 Olympic Games in London.
There, however, Yana was able to take only 17th place, not enough to get into the final competitions in the individual championship.
But two years before that, she managed to win a bronze medal at the Olympic Games - youth.
Another gymnast, only this time athletic - Irina Sazonova.
If the ways of emigration of the athletes mentioned earlier can be called standard, then the choice of Irina's family is very unusual - Iceland.
Ira is a pupil of the Volgograd sports school.
Naturally, in Iceland, she immediately became the national champion.
True, Ira still trains in Russia - she specially comes to her homeland in order not to lose her skills.
In Rio, she did not perform as well as she would have liked.
The best place is 40 in the individual all-around.
There is very little information about swimmer Maria Ugolkova in the Russian information space.
For a very long time, Maria has been living and training in Switzerland.
However, for a long time she performed under the Russian flag, showing good results - there was even a national record at a distance of 200 meters butterfly.
In 2015, she received Swiss citizenship and began to perform under the red and white flag.
In Rio, her best performance is 14th place in the 4×100 relay.
To get to the games, the girl launched a crowdfunding project, thanks to which she was able to collect about 6 thousand francs, which allowed her to pay for the preparation for the Olympics.
31-year-old freestyle wrestler Adam Batirov spent almost his entire career under the Russian flag.
During this time, the native of Khasavyurt managed to become a three-time medalist of the European Championships, the champion of Russia, the master of sports of Russia of international class.
When he stopped getting into our national team, it was time to think about changing his citizenship.
For several years, the talented wrestler disappeared from the sports platforms.
A triumphant return took place at the 2016 Asian Championships - Batirov already represented Bahrain, for which he won a gold medal and received a ticket to the Olympics in Rio.
Even less is known about another ex-Russian, Mikhail Kudinov, at home than even about the Swiss swimmer Maria Ugolkova.
The fact is that his parents emigrated from Vladivostok to New Zealand when the boy was very young.
It was there that Mikhail began to engage in gymnastics.
He has not achieved great success at the international level.
In Rio, his best result was 40th place in the qualification on parallel bars.
But for New Zealand, even getting to the Olympic Games in artistic gymnastics is already a breakthrough.
When Nastya, born in Moscow in 1985, was only 9 years old, her family emigrated to Israel.
There, the girl continued her synchronized swimming lessons, showing high results at the national level.
In 2014, at the European Championships in Berlin, the girl took 6th place in synchronized swimming.
In a duet with Evgenia Tetelbaum, Anastasia took eighth place.
In the solo program, she was fifth.
Like Anastasia, 23-year-old Dmitry Kreuter plays for the Israeli national team.
When the boy was only 6 years old, his mother decided to immigrate to Israel.
In 2009, at the age of 17, Dmitry already became the champion of the country.
In the same year, he won the World Youth Championship.
A year later, Croyter won gold at the Youth Olympic Games in Singapore.
In addition to the high jump, Dmitry is engaged in the long jump and triple jump.
31-year-old Albert is another native of Khasavyurt, who, after long performances for Russia, decided to change his sports citizenship.
However, unlike Batirov, Albert chose Romania, which he will represent in Rio.
In Russia, he played for the School of Higher Sports Mastery of Krasnoyarsk, in 2011 even becoming the champion of the country.
28-year-old Oleg Antonov was born in Moscow in the family of the player of the USSR national volleyball team Yaroslav Antonov.
Just a year before the birth of his son, Yaroslav was recognized as the best volleyball player on the planet.
He soon decided to pursue a career in Italy.
There the family remained for permanent residence.
In 2015, as part of the national team, he became a bronze medalist of the European Championship, held in the territory of his new homeland.
Khadzhiev was born in Chechnya in 1994 and was caught with his family in the midst of the war.
Ten years later, the parents decided to emigrate.
The original target was Norway, but it was not possible to get into this northern country - I had to go to France, to Nice.
There Zelimkhan continued to study freestyle wrestling.
He soon won the World Junior Championships and later qualified for the Olympics.
In Rio, he will be the only representative of France in the wrestling tournament.
And again freestyle wrestling, and again a former Russian.
This time it will be about a native of North Ossetia, who emigrated to Spain - about Taimuraz Friev.
At the end of December 2012, he was granted Spanish citizenship, and currently plays for the national team of this country.
Before that, however, the 30-year-old athlete managed to score high results in Russia.
He won the bronze medal at the 2007 and 2008 National Championships.
Tired of not getting into the national team, Taimuraz decided to change his sports citizenship.
The last on our list is the Chechen boxer, born in 1995 in the capital of Dagestan, Makhachkala, Artur Biyarslanov.
When the boy was ten years old, his parents took the family through Azerbaijan to Canada.
There, Arthur, on the advice of his older brother, began boxing.
Since then, Arthur has become the champion of Canada three times, and in 2012 he became the world champion among youth.
In 2015, Biyarslanov won gold at the Pan American Games, the first for his new homeland since 1975.
Head of the Presidential Administration of the Russian Federation Anton Vaino.
On Friday, August 12, Vladimir Putin appointed Anton Vaino as the head of the presidential administration of Russia.
Previously, this position was held by Sergey Ivanov.
"The head of state by his decree appointed Anton Vaino as the Head of the Presidential Administration of the Russian Federation, relieving him of his post," the decree signed by Putin and published on the Kremlin's website says.
Since May 2012, Vaino has been Deputy Head of the Presidential Administration of the Russian Federation.
Anton Eduardovich Vaino was born on February 17, 1972 in Tallinn.
Father - Eduard Vaino, Chairman of the Cuba-Russia Business Council at the Chamber of Commerce and Industry of the Russian Federation and Vice President for External Relations and Interaction with Shareholders of AvtoVAZ OJSC.
Grandfather - Karl Vaino - from 1978 to 1988 - First Secretary of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of Estonia.
In 1996 he graduated from the Moscow State Institute of International Relations of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Russia, Faculty of International Relations.
From 1996 to 2001, he worked at the Russian Embassy in Japan, then at the Second Department of Asia of the Russian Foreign Ministry.
From 2002 to 2004, he held various positions in the Protocol Office of the President of the Russian Federation.
From 2004 to 2007 - Deputy Head of the Protocol and Organizational Department of the President of the Russian Federation.
From 2007 to 2007 - First Deputy Head of Protocol of the President of the Russian Federation.
From October 2007 to April 2008 - Deputy Chief of Staff of the Government of the Russian Federation.
On April 25, 2008, he was appointed Chief of Protocol of the Prime Minister of the Russian Federation, Deputy Chief of Staff of the Government of the Russian Federation.
Since December 27, 2011 - Minister of the Russian Federation - Chief of Staff of the Government of the Russian Federation.
On May 22, 2012, he was appointed Deputy Head of the Presidential Administration of the Russian Federation.
He is fluent in English and Japanese.
Full State Counsellor of the Russian Federation of the 1st class (class rank was assigned by the Decree of the President of the Russian Federation of January 22, 2008)
Certificate of Merit of the President of the Russian Federation (February 16, 2012) for merits in ensuring the activities of the Government of the Russian Federation and many years of conscientious work.
Gratitude of the President of the Russian Federation (November 24, 2005) for his merits in the preparation and holding of solemn events dedicated to the 60th anniversary of Victory in the Great Patriotic War.
He is married and has a son.
