Moscow's reaction at this point was fierce.
Mr Putin erupted in an angry tirade, accusing Ankara of stabbing Moscow in the back.
The insult was even stronger based on the alleged friend.
Restoring real trust will be difficult, probably impossible.
Russian public opinion has also changed since November.
For months, the state-controlled media carried out a stunning, all-out offensive against Ankara.
Suddenly, it seemed that the Turks should be considered guilty of everything.
The most serious were accusations from senior officials that Mr. Erdogan's own family had profited from the illegal oil trade from areas of Syria controlled by the so-called Islamic State.
He denied it emphatically.
But in St. Petersburg, there was an official signal that it was time to move on.
After all, this meeting only happened because Mr. Putin received an apology he demanded from President Erdogan.
Russia could claim a victory of its kind.
For Ankara, the benefits of declaring a truce are clear.
First and foremost, Erdogan needs all the friends he can get after he was nearly ousted from office last month in a coup attempt.
The repeated terrorist attacks on Turkey clearly shocked him too.
There is also an economic reason.
Russian sanctions have hit hard — especially the ban on charter flights, which typically bring several million Russian tourists to the Turkish coast each year.
The number fell sharply by almost 90%.
As for Russia, tour operators and charter companies here will certainly feel relieved when flights finally resume.
They bet on the peak end of the season in the Mediterranean.
And even this week, state television predicted cheaper fruits and vegetables as soon as Turkish imports of agricultural products were allowed again.
"Tourists there, tomatoes back here," as the report said in the Vedomosti newspaper.
But the visit also had additional political value for Moscow.
Ankara is angry with the West for what it sees as a weak response to a coup attempt.
Add to that its lingering discontent with the snail's pace of talk of joining the EU and Mr. Putin's move — which seeks to take advantage of the coolness and gradually destroy Turkish ties with the West.
The Russian leader, of course, won bonus points with Ankara for calling for support for elected authorities in the wake of the coup attempt.
Keep in mind, this is a given for Moscow, which has its own deep-seated fear of regime change.
So, the summit at this gleaming palace on the seashore allowed Russia and Turkey to present what one analyst described to me as an "alliance of the bad": two countries that feel rejected and humiliated by the West join forces.
