Pokémon Go, a worthy hunt for health and happiness
It's fascinating to watch the world change.
That teens and children no longer go outside to play, preferring to spend their free time looking at screens, has been a complaint to many over the past decade.
Pokemon Go pulls people off the couch and engages them in some physical activity.
Screen time was initially limited to the TV, then video games and more recently smartphones.
It's so great to see that technology and outdoor activity are not mutually exclusive.
I'm referring, of course, to the craze that is Pokémon Go, an application based on characters originally created for video games in the 1990s (which later spawned a series of cartoons, playing cards, and other offshoots).
Like many other pop culture phenomena, all this lost its former relevance a little earlier than this new game became available in the United States, Australia and New Zealand in early July.
The launch in other countries at the time was delayed due to a massive response that overloaded the servers.
In a matter of days, Pokémon Go had more users than Tinder and almost as many as Twitter.
So how does it work?
In a nutshell, players with smartphones go looking for Pokémon that are tracked by GPS and, once detected, can be 'photographed' (through a screenshot on your phone) or 'caught'.
The generation that played the game as they were younger joined the craze by pulling away from the couches to search.
In the U.S., the game has led to a significant increase in the number of steps taken by the "average" person on a daily basis.
Cardiogram, an Apple Watch app that tracks 35,000 users, recently told the Washington Post that within two days of the game's launch, the number of people it tracked who performed 30-minute exercises daily jumped from 45 percent to 53 percent.
The company doesn't know who's playing Pokémon Go, it just sees the raw data on the progression of the levels.
Many health campaigns urging people to "find 30 minutes," "get off the couch," and "be active every day" have failed because most health messages are boring and are spoken out by people who look unhappy.
However, the importance of exercise cannot be underestimated.
Those who exercise regularly reduce the chances of developing cancer or depression.
Physical activity helps with weight correction, high blood pressure, diabetes and another long list of benefits, too long to cite here.
But the beauty of Pokémon Go is that it pulls people out into the street to do what they love.
Thus, the three foundations of health are covered: movement, fresh air and sunlight and joy.
Some people even make new friends while hunting.
As usual, there are boring nerds looking for something to complain about.
And yes, someone might stumble upon a door.
So what?
A breakthrough has occurred.
After all, despite the fact that smartphone applications such as Fitbit could previously track our physical activity, they did not give us a reason to practice, as this game gives.
The novelty will get bored, and the use will weaken over time.
However, due to the success of Pokemon, there will be more games that will combine apps and virtual reality with physical activity in the real world, helping many people on the hunt to be more active, in good shape and healthy.
