I have about 3,000 or 4,000 records.
These plates, pictured above (he emailed me a picture, I didn't chase him home), run in lines along the walls of his living room.
His reason for acquiring so many albums and singles stems in part from his disposable income: he can now buy records he couldn't afford when they first came out, and buy back items he sold when he was young and stranded.
"A lot of what I'm buying is late '60s, early '70s, things that came out when I was 11 or 12, things that I was probably too young to buy for," he says.
He agrees that those who buy records are most likely introverts who like their own company, adding: "I don't smoke, I don't drink very much.
That's my flaw.
Wez, 25, who works at Sister Ray, also believes that many of the clients he meets fit the YouGov profile.
He, however, noticed a new wave of people influenced by the media hype, people who had heard about the return and felt obligated to buy their old records.
Judging by the conversations I've had, people got rid of their collection, usually around 1998 or 1999.
Customers who once sold their vinyl to buy CDs are now selling their CDs to redeem their records," he says.
This may explain the boom among vinyl revivalists of a certain age.
What about the supposed emotional importance of the records?
It only takes a few seconds in a store like Phonica to realize that record stores offer a comfortable company to people with similar views.
According to Huez, some older customers, in particular, are offended by the cashless payment system.
Some vinyl lovers may feel shocked by the digital world and prefer to retire to the constancy of familiar record envelopes, objects that evoke memories of serene adolescence.
