At a court hearing this week, Authorities in Calais said the state should be able to demolish a total of 72 makeshift shops where people inside the camp sell goods ranging from cigarettes to energy drinks, offer a haircut or sell tea for 50 cents (40p) or simple meals for a few euros in homemade restaurants.
Calais Prefecture has said these sites should be demolished because they represent a parallel economy that does not pay taxes, and because they carry fire and health risks.
Humanitarian groups told the court that shops and restaurants were vital, saying the free meals offered by the pro-government association and other groups did not provide enough food for the camp's growing population.
They have commented that makeshift shops and restaurants often provide shelter and free food to those in need.
The Lille court ruled that there was no legal basis to kick out the people running the 72 makeshift shops, but said the problems of the prefecture of Calais "were fully understood".
Judge Jean-François Molla said groceries, cafes and restaurants played a much bigger role than just feeding people who "live in extremely precarious conditions".
He said the spaces provided tranquil meeting points for refugees and volunteers.
One of the sites that was in danger of demolition was the camp's Jungle Book children's café, which doesn't work for profit and offers 200 lunches a day, English and French classes, and asylum counseling for hundreds of vulnerable unaccompanied minors in the camp.
More than 170,000 people signed a petition to protect the children's café.
A letter sent to the Guardian said its closure "would be a disaster for these children, some of whom are under the age of eight".
Two charities, Aid to Refugees and L'Auberge des Migrants, on Friday estimated that numbers at The Jungle Camp had grown to more than 9,000 people — the highest ever — after a sharp increase in newcomers over the summer.
