Britain settles for silver in rugby 7s after Fiji's masterclass allows them to take gold
Britain's impressive streak in Rugby 7 was crushingly halted at a final obstacle by Fiji's side in Thursday night's final when they were completely crushed 43-7 at the Deodoro Stadium here in Rio.
Fiji gave a masterclass in possession, passing, evasion, game support, running lines and brute force to win gold – their first Olympic medal of any colour.
The defeat came with a not-too-poor consolation in the form of silver – Britain's third in a day – and they could be proud of their efforts in the first Olympic Rugby 7 tournament, in which they defeated New Zealand, Argentina and South Africa along the way.
A painful beating of the Boks, 7-5 in the semi-finals earlier in the day, could have returned to negatively affect them in the final.
But, despite everything, Fiji in this form defeated the best team of 15 people.
It may be some consolation for Britain – but probably not – that at least one Briton will hang a gold medal around his neck tomorrow: Fiji head coach Ben Ryan, former England chief from Wimbledon.
It was a bit of a journey for the UK.
Eight years ago, under Ryan, they lost every game at the Adelaide Sevens.
Here they lost just one.
These blows will hurt, but the progress is astounding.
Fiji started superbly, deflecting Great Britain's attempts to intercept the ball for fun.
It was like bumping into a convoy of moving buses for Captain Tom Mitchell and company, and the World Series champions went up 5-0 when Osea Kolinisau dived into the corner.
With four minutes on the clock, Gerrir Tuwai added another touchdown down the right flank, which was converted.
12-0 and Great Britain barely touched the ball.
Mitchell's superb interception attempt deterred the mountain man Leon Nakarawa from scoring a third, but that only kept Fiji on track.
In the seventh minute, Jasa Veremalua scored a touchdown in the right corner and Great Britain lost 17-0.
Nakarava added another one after resuming and the clock was still over a minute long... in the first half.
Vatemo Ravovo then broke through several more half-hearted attempts to intercept Britain and stormed the line to get a point.
The conversion led to a 29-0 break.
It looked as if Fiji were born to play rugby 7 while The UK was still mastering the craft.
Which pretty much is.
Great Britain made massive substitutions halfway through the game and they plugged the Fijian dam... for all four minutes, which was good by first-half standards, until Joshua Tuisov passed after a few brilliant Fijian interactions.
Dan Norton grabbed a try for Great Britain by making a touchdown in the left corner to make the score 36-7, but the game had long been in the footsteps of the South Sea Islanders, whose fans sang, waved flags and danced in the stands.
It was impossible not to admire Fiji's joyful approach.
Mata William embellished the Fijian cake, which didn't need embellishment, with another attempt in the final seconds.
The whistle sounded, the Fijians embraced, and Britain fell to the turf, completely defeated.
Earlier in the day, Fiji defeated Japan 20-5 in their semi-finals, with Britain slightly beating South Africa in a tense semi-final of one attempt each – the difference is British realization.
Kyle Brown put the Boks ahead in the first half, but Dan Norton, with some great footwork, tore up the line and scored under the beams in the second half.
A brilliant last interception attempt from Marcus Watson, the brother of England's 15th-sided team, Anthony, secured victory — and ultimately a silver medal.
Helen Glover and Heather Stanning are inspired to win rowing by a coach's battle with cancer.
There won't be more exhilarating gold at these games, and that says something.
From the first movement to the last, 220 hard climbs in history, Helen Glover and Heather Stanning found the added meaning of their golden moment at Estacio da Lagoa.
Although they were the two who pulled the oars, there were three voices in this boat, coach Robin Williams' echo was always there while they were aiming for a second consecutive Olympic gold in women's pairs, the first women in the annals of British sports to reach such a height.
Their superiority was absolute, after all it was their 39th undefeated performance, again unprecedented.
What we see is that the two brilliant female athletes gliding across the surface with the elegance of swans do not fully reflect the nature of triumph.
Behind each gold rowed a battalion of ready hands, contributing to the gradually increasing victories that are important, and there are no hands that were more important than the hands of the coach who, 30 months ago, when he was diagnosed with cancer, did not know whether he would live to see this day.
As he said, it was a dangerous business.
I had bladder cancer, which is one of the things they can operate on, and they did.
If they don't, it goes everywhere.
It could have been a pretty bad situation.
It changes your views a little bit for the future.
Williams was diagnosed in December 2013.
The trio was fortunate to be able to start treatment in early 2014 in the offseason, keeping the schedule gap minimal if it could be the right expression in circumstances like these.
I needed payment, so I needed to get well quickly.
It was an incentive.
I was in the hospital and walking around the ward — 20 feet, 30 feet, 50 feet at a time, even though they said a few steps were enough.
Here's how it starts.
Rowing itself is a journey, but that makes it a little bigger.
In the instant after the win, their first thoughts were of Williams, who spent a nervous morning talking a little more than usual in an attempt to overcome his own experiences.
Stanning, a captain in an artillery regiment serving in Afghanistan, said: "I was an emotional wreck this week, maybe it's a little too much, but it means so much."
It only confirms how much it means to me, how much Helen and I worked and Robin too.
It's been a fantastic three years with Helen and Robin.
Without Robin, we would be nobody, so thank you so much to him, he's the best coach in the world.
I couldn't ask for a better partner to train or a better coach.
Helen Glover and Heather Stanning haven't lost a single race in five years.
This pair sets a tense rhythm that their competitors have never been able to match.
Even in the final 500 yards, as the New Zealand and Denmark teams began to approach, Stanning and Glover had too much in reserve.
We were very much in phase.
Helen called, 'Stay in the process, stay in the process.'
Now it is very important not to get carried away.
We had a good start and at the same time we didn't try to do anything amazing.
We weren't expecting fireworks today, we were just expecting that we could paddle well and go out and win this race, which we did.
It will take a year for the couple to decide their future.
Glover needs to be at next month's wedding, her own with TV adventurer Steve Backshall.
Now she just wants to enjoy the moment.
I didn't want to say it was my last race.
That would mean too much pressure.
In London, it took about six months to realize that I had become an Olympic champion.
It was all so new and I was so tense.
It took about four minutes.
I feel so much better," she said.
The government extended the deadline for the destruction of sanctioned products
The government extended until the end of 2017 the deadline for the destruction of food products prohibited for import into Russia.
The corresponding resolution was signed by Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev, it was published on the official portal of legal information.
The embargo against countries that imposed anti-Russian sanctions because of the situation in Ukraine was introduced in our country in August 2014.
Subsequently, the ban was repeatedly extended, now it is valid until December 31, 2017.
It is forbidden to import into Russia certain types of agricultural products, raw materials and food from the Usa, the European Union, Canada, Australia, Norway, Ukraine, Albania, Montenegro, Iceland and Liechtenstein.
In particular, meat and meat products, fish, seafood, vegetables, fruits and dairy products were banned.
Disposal of food imported into the country in circumvention of the embargo has been carried out in Russia since August 2015.
Only in the first quarter of 2016, about 100 tons of prohibited products were withdrawn from sale.
