The WTO Panel of Arbitrators found that Russian import duties on paper, refrigerators and palm oil are contrary to the rules of the organization.
Import rates exceed the obligations assumed by Russia when joining the WTO.
"This is the first time that the WTO has made a decision against the Russian Federation," the statement on the official website of the organization said.
However, the arbitrators stressed in their opinion that the EU did not provide sufficient evidence that Russia's measures "were systematic" or "comprehensive."
Russia, in turn, promised to adapt import duties on paper and refrigerators in the near future.
This is stated in the message of the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia.
On July 4, it was reported that Kiev intends to complain to the World Trade Organization about the actions of Russia, which imposed additional restrictions on the transit of Ukrainian goods.
This is stated in the statement of the government of Ukraine.
In May, the Financial Times wrote that the behavior of the United States in resolving controversial issues in the WTO undermines the principles of discussion adopted in the organization.
A similar statement was made by Brazil, Japan, the European Union and other WTO members because of the refusal of the Americans to approve south Korean judge Jang Song Hwa for a second term.
In this regard, Russia will not apply to the WTO on the issue of Western sanctions imposed against the Russian Federation.
The WTO is an international organization established in January 1995 to liberalize international trade.
Now it consists of 162 countries.
