In Poland, they admit that they will not buy fuel from Gazprom.
The state Polish oil and gas company PGNIG does not exclude that in a few years gas supplies from the Russian Federation may become unattractive for it due to the reorientation to fuel from Norway and other countries.
This was announced by the vice-president of the Polish company for finance Bogusław Mazzec.
His words are reported by TASS.
"It may happen that we will not buy gas at all (from Gazprom), we are now diversifying our supplies.
Within the next four years, the main directions of supply for us will be the East, raw materials from LNG terminals and Norway," Mažec said.
Currently, Gazprom occupies a dominant position in the supply of gas to Poland.
On Friday, August 12, PGNIG reported that the Russian supplier in the first half of 2016 supplied it with almost 5.3 billion cubic meters. m of gas, which is 30% higher than in 2015.
The share of the Russian gas giant in PGNIG's purchases rose to 49.8% compared to 40% a year earlier.
Recall that on July 22, the Antimonopoly Authority of Poland did not agree on the creation of a joint venture of Gazprom and its European partners in the construction of the Nord Stream-2 gas pipeline.
At the same time, a month earlier, Poland left a request to Gazprom for the supply of 11 billion cubic meters. m of gas through Nord Stream-2.
This was stated by deputy chairman of the board of the holding Alexander Medvedev.
The auction for the capacity of Nord Stream 2 will be held in 2017, and in the autumn of 2016 it is planned to hold an auction for its laying.
At the end of May, it was reported that Gazprom does not plan to take any action in connection with the intentions of the Polish side to abandon long-term contracts for the supply of gas from Russia after 2022, said Alexander Medvedev, deputy chairman of the company's board.
He recalled that in the first quarter of this year, the Poles only increased gas purchases from the Russian Federation by 42%.
The deputy chairman of Gazprom added that the very fact of the Polish PGNIG filing an application with the Stockholm Arbitration Court does not mean the termination of negotiations.
Earlier, the Polish company appealed to the court to achieve a reduction in the purchase price of Russian gas.
Recall, the Commissioner of the Polish government for gas and energy infrastructure Piotr Naimski said that the Polish authorities decided not to extend the contract with Gazprom for the supply of gas.
Poland's contract with Gazprom was signed in 1996 and expires in 2022.
In March, the Polish government's commissioner for gas and energy infrastructure, Piotr Naimski, said that his country could refuse to supply blue fuel from the east in six years.
According to him, Warsaw plans to build a new terminal for the supply of liquefied natural gas Baltic Pipe, which will connect the country with the Norwegian shelf.
Nord Stream 2 provides for the construction of two lines of the offshore gas pipeline with a total capacity of 55 billion cubic meters of gas per year from Russia to Germany along the bottom of the Baltic Sea.
