The UN is investigating the use of chemical weapons in Syria.
A special UN commission is investigating the possible use of toxic gas in rebel-held areas of the Syrian city of Aleppo.
All parties to the conflict deny the use of chlorine, but the UN special envoy for Syria, Steffan de Mistura, considers the fact of what happened indisputable.
Such statements were made on the eve of the third round of intra-Syrian talks, which are due to begin in late August in Geneva.
UN experts have launched an investigation into reports of the use of chemical weapons in the Syrian city of Aleppo.
The first information about the terrorist attack with the use of toxic gas, presumably chlorine, appeared on August 2.
Then the opposition said that in the area where a Russian military transport helicopter was shot down the day before, aviation dropped bombs with a toxic substance, but in Moscow these accusations were called planting.
Later, the Russian Ministry of Defense blamed the incident on the opposition group Harakat Nur al-Din al-Zinki.
Soon it became known that there were two bombs filled with toxic gas.
This was confirmed to the BBC by one of the victims.
"A few minutes later, I smelled gas, my eyes began to burn, it became difficult to breathe," the publication quoted an eyewitness as saying.
As a result of the attack, at least 7 people were killed, 23 were hospitalized.
If the fact of using poison gas is confirmed by experts, the actions will be regarded as a war crime.
The UN special envoy for Syria, Staffan de Mistura, told reporters: "There is a lot of evidence that this really happened."
The inadmissibility of the use of chlorine for military purposes is prescribed in the Convention on the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (CWC).
Despite the fact that all parties to the Syrian conflict deny the use of toxic gases, in 2015 human rights activists recorded 35 cases of the use of chlorine by the Syrian army against the "moderate opposition".
The situation in Aleppo is complicated by the fact that shelling of its areas is carried out daily, and terrorists prevent the withdrawal of residents from the city.
According to Reuters, the UN expects Russia to establish a "humanitarian pause" in hostilities.
The current regime of daily three-hour lull in the organization is considered "insufficient to help almost 2 million civilians trapped."
Staffan de Mistura's humanitarian adviser, Jan Egeland, said a 48-hour ceasefire would be required every week to bring aid to and evacuate the sick and wounded from the city.
"We have to send bulk cargo with a convoy of trucks in an area where the roads are almost destroyed, and those that remain are mined," mr. Egeland said. "But the Russian delegation confirmed its readiness to sit down with us at the negotiating table."
Consultations in Geneva between representatives of the United States and Russia on the establishment of a "humanitarian pause" continue.
How Russia opened "humanitarian windows" in Aleppo.
Amid the ongoing battle for Aleppo, Syria's second-largest city, Russia on August 11 announced a three-hour cessation of hostilities that will be in place daily starting Thursday.
The creation of "humanitarian windows" is intended to provide conditions for the delivery of medicines, food and basic necessities to the city.
The decision of the Ministry of Defense of the Russian Federation was made against the background of increasing international pressure on Moscow with a demand to curtail the military operation and contribute to the resumption of the negotiation process.
As a result of a series of explosions at the resorts of Thailand, four people were killed.
Several explosions thundered in the south of Thailand on Friday morning.
As a result of the attack, four people were killed, 19 were injured.
The epicenter of the explosions fell on the city of Hua Hin.
Among the victims were ten foreigners, citizens of four states, there are no Russians among them.
None of the terrorist groups has yet claimed responsibility for the incident, but the country's Interior Ministry was quick to declare that the Islamists were not involved in it.
Several people have already been detained on suspicion of organizing explosions.
According to preliminary data from local police, the scale and features of the explosions indicate that they were directed against the military leaders of the country.
The attacks occurred in popular tourist resorts, including Patong Beach in the Phuket area and the cities of Hua Hin, Trang and Surat Thani.
After the military junta came to power in the country in 2014, economic growth fell from 7.2% (2012) to 2.8% (2015), but tourism remained one of the few industries that demonstrated development.
In 2016, the country has already been visited by 14 million people, which is 1.5 million more than in 2015.
The first suspects in the preparation and organization of attacks have already been detained, police Colonel Krisana Patanacharoen said.
It is too early to talk about the goals, he added, but the country's Interior Ministry "is confident that they are not connected with international extremist groups."
It is too early to draw conclusions," Said Mr. Patanacharoen. -
But we do know that these incidents are not directly related to any kind of terrorism, in fact they are local sabotage, and we are trying to establish the identities of those who were behind them.
The explosions occurred on the birthday of Queen Sikrit of Thailand.
The Thai junta considers the protection of the monarchy one of its top priorities, so the incident is most likely directed against it.
According to police general Sithichay Srisopacharoenrat, the bombs were detonated remotely half an hour apart.
They were hidden inside trees in busy streets filled with tourists dining in restaurants.
It is already known that one of the four dead was a Thai girl who sold street food.
The identities of the remaining victims are still unknown, but it is known that they are residents of four foreign countries.
According to the Royal Thai Police, among them are four German citizens, three Dutch citizens, two Italian citizens and an Austrian citizen.
There are no Russians among the victims of the explosions, the press service of the Federal Agency for Tourism reported.
Local experts also attribute the explosions to the August 7 referendum, in which 61.4% of the country's population supported the draft of the new constitution.
It was prepared by a constitutional drafting commission appointed by the military junta.
Voters had to decide whether they supported a system in which the upper house of parliament was fully appointed by the military and had a significant role in electing the country's prime minister.
The new system has been adopted and will be tested for the first time in the 2017 parliamentary elections.
Recall, on May 22, 2014, a military coup took place in Thailand under the leadership of the country's army commander Prayut Chan-o-cha.
This step, he said, prompted the army by the ongoing political crisis and the lack of progress in negotiations between the government and the opposition.
The military created the National Council for Peace and Order, imposed curfews and censorship, and dispersed protesters and the upper house of parliament.
How Bangkok found itself in a state of emergency
The Thai government, led by Prime Minister Yingluck Shinawatra, in January 2014 declared a state of emergency in Bangkok and the provinces adjacent to the capital.
The special regime lasted 60 days.
As in Bangkok, two explosions thundered.
In January 2014, in the center of Bangkok, at the Victory Monument, where one of the main protests took place, two explosions occurred, as a result of which 28 people were injured, five of them were in critical condition.
The explosions were carried out by unknown persons on motorcycles.
Authorities have stepped up security measures in the capital and enlisted military forces to protect demonstrators.
In Sukhoi Log, the development of conditions began.
As it became known to "Kommersant", the government was invited to agree on the draft terms of the auction for the Sukhoi Log gold deposit with the preservation of two key restrictions.
It is proposed not to allow companies where 25% or more belongs to foreigners, and those applicants whose capital will not include at least 25% of state participation.
Industry participants do not expect the government to rewrite the terms, noting that many players do not risk taking on a complex and expensive project.
The auction can be announced in August, and held in October.
The Ministry of Natural Resources has submitted to the government a draft order and terms of the auction for the largest undeveloped gold deposit in Russia Sukhoi Log (Irkutsk region, reserves and resources - 130 million ounces), two sources familiar with the situation told Kommersant.
The project was introduced on Wednesday evening, one of them specifies.
The Ministry of Natural Resources confirmed to Kommersant that the project has been submitted to the government.
A representative of Deputy Prime Minister Alexander Khloponin, who oversees subsoil use, told Kommersant that the project has not yet been submitted to the official's office.
"The auction can be announced as early as August, immediately after the release of the government order, and taking into account the deadline for collecting applications from potential participants (at least 45 days), the tender may take place as early as October," the Ministry of Natural Resources said.
According to Kommersant, the draft retained two key requirements for potential participants, spelled out in the version that was sent for approval to the ministries and federal executive bodies in July (Kommersant has).
The first is the presence in the capital of applicants of at least 25% of state participation.
The second is the denial of access to the auction for companies under the control of foreign investors, based on the understanding of FZ-57 on foreign investments in strategic companies.
According to the two articles of the Federal Law specified in the draft, as Kommersant already wrote on August 2, companies whose beneficiaries (25% of shares and above) are not tax residents of the Russian Federation or have dual citizenship may not be allowed to participate in the auction.
The government has the right to impose such restrictions, since Sukhoi Log belongs to the subsoil of federal significance (reserves of more than 50 tons of gold).
The Ministry of Natural Resources confirmed that the draft "contains restrictions on the admission of foreign companies," but declined to comment on the details before the government order.
The requirement for state participation in the capital of the auction participants was put forward by the Irkutsk region, kommersant was told in December 2015 by the Ministry of Natural Resources and confirmed later by the governor of the region Sergey Levchenko, noting that it was sent to the Ministry of Natural Resources by his predecessor Sergey Yeroshchenko, "who had agreements on investment projects with Rostec."
Who lobbied for the restriction on the admission of foreigners, the interlocutors of "Kommersant" do not specify.
"But this is in the spirit of the times: do not give up control in the largest gold deposit in Russia against the background of Western sanctions," says the interlocutor of "Kommersant", familiar with the preparation of the auction.
The head of the Ministry of Natural Resources, Sergei Donskoy, said on August 1 that foreigners "can go to the consortium" if the applicants attract them "as a financial structure, technological partners."
Kommersant's interlocutors consider it unlikely that the government will adjust the conditions.
The main contender for Sukhoi Log in the industry is considered to be a consortium of the largest gold miner of the Russian Federation PJSC Polyus, controlled by Suleyman Kerimov's son Said, and Rostec.
As Kommersant wrote, in July, the partners created the SL Gold joint venture, where Polyus has 51% of the shares, the Rostec structure RT-GR has 49%.
Rostec declined to comment, Polyus told Kommersant that they are "certainly interested in this asset" and have all the necessary competencies and resources for its development.
"But the final decision on the possibility and format of our participation will be made after the announcement of the conditions," Polyus added.
ALROSA may participate in the auction, but the decision is up to the Russian government, Kommersant's sources said.
The possibility of participation in the development of Sukhoi Log was stated by the Russian GV Gold and the Canadian Kinross, which develops assets in Chukotka, while Polymetal and Nordgold, according to Kommersant, are not interested in the asset.
The head of the Union of Gold Producers of the Russian Federation, Sergey Kashuba, in December 2015 estimated Kommersant's investment in Sukhoi Log at $ 2.5-4 billion.
Most potential applicants are deterred not only by the volume of investments, but also by the complexity of the project: serious additional exploration of reserves and technologies for working with complex ores are needed, Kommersant's interlocutors in the industry explain.
The largest M&A transaction was launched in the pension market - KIT Finance Pension Administrator launched the process of merging four controlled NPFs.
As a result, on the basis of "Gazfond Pension Savings" will be created NPF with a volume of savings of about 373 billion rubles.
The launch of the procedure for merging four pension funds - KIT Finance, Promagrofond, Nasledie and Gazfond Pension Savings - was announced yesterday by the owner of 100% of the funds KIT Finance Pension Administrator LLC.
"Reorganization is carried out in coordination with the Central Bank in compliance with the requirement of non-deterioration of the terms of existing contracts," the company said.
The merger is carried out on the basis of "Gazfond Pension Savings".
As the general director of this NPF Oleg Bialoshitsky notes, the merger of funds allows us to solve several problems: expanding the geography of presence, concentrating resources for development, reducing costs, replicating the best practices of each of the funds and optimizing corporate governance.
According to him, the approximate deadline for the completion of consolidation is the second quarter of 2017.
As a result of the merger, NPF Gazfond Pension Savings will become the largest player in the OPS market.
As of March 31, the volume of pension savings of the merging funds exceeded 373 billion rubles.
As follows from the reports on the website of the funds, the beneficiaries of their owner - KIT Finance Pension Administrator - are currently Anatoly Gavrilenko (through controlled LLC owns 65%) and NPF Gazfond (35%).
However, the group launched the merger itself much later than its competitors.
Thus, NPF Future, controlled by the O1 group, absorbed Stalfond at the beginning of this year.
Currently, this combined NPF joins the Uralsib and Russian Standard funds.
"Unification into a single structure, in addition to reducing costs, is necessary to solve structural problems," said Nikolai Sidorov, general director of NPF Future.
Active work on the consolidation of funds has been going on since April in the pension group "Safmar" - NPF "European", "Education and Science" and "Regionfond" should join NPF "SAFMAR" by the end of this year.
In 2017, they will be joined by NPF "Trust".
"The merger of funds will have the effect of strengthening control over risks, operational processes and expenses," the SAFMAR pension group noted.
The pause in the pooling of funds, which was withstood by KIT Finance Pension Administrator, can be caused by several reasons, experts say.
Until recently, NPFs could not buy back more than 40% of the volume of infrastructure bonds issued, in which the group was actively placed.
After amending the resolution of the Central Bank in March of this year, there are no more such restrictions on a number of issuers that meet the requirements of the regulator.
If necessary, one major player can buy out the entire issue," said Yuri Nogin, Director of acra's Financial Institutions Ratings Group.
Several heads of NPFs from the top 15 in terms of assets call another possible reason for the pause the division of spheres of influence and, as a result, personnel appointments in a single fund, which had to be agreed by the owners of the group.
Yesterday Anatoly Gavrilenko was unavailable for comment.
On the request of "Kommersant" in the NPF "Gazfond" also did not respond.
Although the consolidation of funds is a time-consuming and expensive undertaking, over a long distance this decision will be justified.
As the general director of the consulting company "Pension Partner" Sergey Okolesnov notes, "Gazfond Pension Savings" has fewer outflows, the accession will stabilize the base of other funds of the group.
At the same time, the more successful experience of KIT Finance and Promagrofond in building retail sales of OPS, as well as the use of more modern software, will be in demand.
