The kindest Disney movie "Pete and His Dragon" was released in Russia.
Beautiful views of New Zealand, a touching dragon, a heart-wrenching story and country songs are enough to believe in old-fashioned magic again, says ELENA KRAVTSUN.
The frightened baby was picked up by a dragon, who became a human cub and a gentle nanny, and a devoted friend.
Pete names his buddy Elliot, after the puppy from the book of fairy tales, plays catch-up with him and falls asleep in a hug.
Six years later, he, overgrown and in a loincloth, can no longer be distinguished from another clever forest tomboy - Mowgli.
In this form, Pete is discovered by the red-haired female huntsman Grace (Bryce Dallas Howard), while the brigade of Gavin (Karl Urban), her husband's brother, aggressively fells the forest.
Now she will have not only to believe in the existence of the dragon, but also to help save it.
Pete takes a crash course in "being human" surrounded by idyllic Americans who wear cowboy shirts, a moral code in their hearts and smile more dazzlingly than in any advertisement.
No character looks or acts too awful for the viewer to truly begin to hate or fear them.
Even Gavin, who opened the hunt for an atypical inhabitant of the forests under his control, is far from an incorrigible villain.
The huge fluffy dragon also turned out not to be scary at all, with a kind bulldog muzzle, an airliner wingspan and the ability to become invisible.
The dragon amusingly rumbles, purrs, even grunts and, fortunately, does not speak, but you want to stroke it all the time, this compares favorably with all the famous cinematic dragons.
The visual image of Elliot and his manner of holding on provide such a high degree of emotional involvement that in the most tense moments, not only small spectators, but also adults begin to desperately sob in three streams.
Surprisingly good and young Oakes Figley in the role of Pete, torn between a possible family and a real friend.
And Robert Redford masterfully betrays a canonical grandfather, whom literally every child would be happy to have.
How did director David Lowry manage to make a fantastically cute remake of the forgotten Disney film Pete's Dragon, mediocre from nose to tail tip and remembered only for a mix of animation and feature films, and make it the most soulful film of the summer?
Nothing short of a miracle helped.
In his painting, Lowry from the original, in fact, took only two things: the orphan Pete and the dragon.
The musical numbers and most of the strange jokes were left behind.
In this kind fairy tale, features borrowed from "Bambi", "E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial" and many other sweet to the heart of children's paintings are read.
Disney studio continues to successfully expand the gallery of high-quality remakes of the XXI century.
Of course, Pete and the Dragon isn't as stunningly beautiful as The Jungle Book, and it doesn't have the skilled villain that Cate Blanchett turned out to be as the stepmother in the new Cinderella.
But this naïve film no less successfully helps to believe in miracles and goodness in the best Disney traditions.
By the way, the director Lowry will receive the keys to the magical Disney castle once again - for the feature film adaptation of the story of "Peter Pan".
Worked out in "Pete and His Dragon" tandem David Lowry and screenwriter Toby Halbrooks entered a new ambitious project about a non-growing boy based on the fairy tale of the same name by James Barry.
RBC journalist Alexander Sokolov will be charged with a new charge
