Kommersant correspondent ALEXANDER SILBERT lived the life of an Olympian in the Olympic Village, inspected the house of the Russian team, had lunch in the local canteen and even passed the WADA test after that.
It seems that life here does not freeze for a second.
Even at night.
The last starts sometimes end after midnight, after which the athletes need another hour and a half or two to return to the Olympic Village.
In addition, settlement and eviction from the village are carried out without stopping, since some athletes complete their performances and leave Brazil, and some, on the contrary, only arrive here.
Well, already at 7:30 in the morning, the heads of all Olympic delegations are drawn to one of the temporary tents.
At these meetings, we usually discuss some operational everyday issues, - says igor Kazikov, head of the sports delegation of the Russian Olympic team. - Despite the fact that the house in which our housed, consider it exemplary - it was put into operation one of the first and demonstrated to all the inspectors, even in it there are now and then some shortcomings.
Sometimes there are problems with hot water, then, excuse me, with toilets.
We fought for cleanliness for a long time.
At first, no one came to clean up.
Then the cleaners began to come, but only pop some substance on the floor, and that's it.
Their floors, you see, are somewhat innovative.
Like, you can't wash them in a human way.
Yes we know these floors - common laminate!
In general, they achieved a change of cleaning company and now everything is OK with this.
The Olympic Village is Such a South Butovo, a sleeping area fenced on one side by mountains, on the other by an impressive moat, sometimes flooded with water.
Well, for reliability, there is still a two-meter iron fence along the entire perimeter, along which machine gunners walk.
In total, the village can accommodate up to 17 thousand people in 3604 apartments located in 31 houses.
On one of the 18-storey buildings hangs a huge Russian flag - this house is completely given to the needs of our team.
Looking at the small foyer at the entrance, you can immediately determine which problems, apparently, are the most pressing for the domestic team.
There are two ads at the front desk: a printed "Please don't throw paper in the toilet!" and a handwritten "I'll accept the gift of badges.
The stand itself is drowned in booklets.
Their cheerful colors contrast with the titles of the brochures: "Memo on infectious diseases for those traveling to Rio de Janeiro", "First aid for drowning, entering the respiratory tract, loss of consciousness - stages of cardiopulmonary resuscitation", "First aid for burns, heat stroke, fractures and bleeding".
The text inside is generally encouraging.
For example, this: "Infection is accompanied by fever and subsequent cure.
However, a favorable outcome does not await everyone.
Of course, in the location of the Russian national team there is a medical center, which at any time is ready to provide qualified assistance to the residents of the house, including relaxing and sports massage.
Opposite the medical center is the actual headquarters of our delegation.
Next to the door is an inspiring poster "No matter what, we will win!".
And, of course, the poems:
All arguments are absolute nonsense!
Only those who fear believe in them.
Let there be fewer of us, the sweeter the taste of victories, Russia will not retreat, will not break!
And for even greater uplifting of spirits, there is an announcement: "Dear brothers and sisters!
With the blessing of His Holiness Patriarch Kirill of Moscow and All Russia, Archpriest Andrei Vladimirovich Alekseev provides spiritual care for the athletes of the Russian Olympic team.
You can order a prayer service and other requirements by phone...
In general, on the territory of the village there is a Center for Meditation and Religious Rites for representatives of all faiths.
Well, the Russians, it turns out, are in a privileged position - they have their own chapel.
Due to the congestion of the elevator from the ninth floor to the fourth, I decided to go down the stairs, which are recommended to be used during a fire.
And in the darkness she tripped over the bodies lying on it.
Apparently, these were sleeping employees of the new cleaning company.
I suppose, in readiness at any moment to rush to wash innovative floors, they decided to arrange a quiet hour directly on the cold steps.
On the fourth floor, I was waiting for a meeting with an old acquaintance - Vitaly Fedorovich Dubko, the coach of our trampoline athletes, who led them to Olympic gold 16 years ago in Sydney.
He and his pupil, European champion Yana Pavlova, kindly agreed to show their rooms.
By and large, there is nothing to complain about, - the honored coach of Russia shares his impressions. - We live in twos, the beds, of course, are almost side by side, but this is not critical.
The bathroom is one for four, but spacious.
The cabinet, of course, is funny, made of fabric, does not inspire confidence, but things can be put.
"No, well, you are guessing, they have run out of tea!" - shrugs tennis player Svetlana Kuznetsova, whom I met in the main dining room.
It is called the main one, if only because it is a space of 2.7 thousand square meters. m and is ready to receive 5 thousand visitors at the same time.
Here they give out 60 thousand servings per day for free.
The menu options are as follows: "The Best of Brazil", "Cuisines of the World", "Asian Dishes" and "Pizza, Pasta".
The last option, as I peeked, is very popular among our volleyball players.
At the same time, for example, I did not find soups in any of the divisions of the giant restaurant.
What soups? Kuznetsova wonders. - No tea!
It's good that I took a Chinese one with me, a custard.
And a kettle.
But in general, so that you understand, our food on the courts is even worse.
Here at least something can be chosen, despite the unbearable monotony.
I personally chose steamed cod and meatballs in tomato sauce.
Next to each dish there is a sign with its name in three languages - English, French and Portuguese, as well as indicating the nutritional value of the product and the presence of allergens in it.
Well, quite, frankly, it was edible.
I don't even understand why there is such a queue all the time at the local McDonald's.
Well-fed, relaxed, we can say "warm" athletes at the exit from the restaurant are waiting for our best friends - representatives of the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA).
They lure cleverly - a quiz, the winner of which gets a T-shirt.
Provoked, you might say!
To get a gift, you need to correctly answer at least eight questions out of ten.
Have questions on the Russian! - A girl from WADA attacked me.
