The Spiritual Administration of Muslims (DUM) of Tatarstan refuses to use the Russian language in mosques.
Yesterday, the plenum of the DUM obliged its imams to conduct Friday sermons only in Tatar in order to force young Tatars to "learn their native language."
The department says that this "in no way infringes" on the rights of Muslims of other nationalities.
Some mosques in Kazan complain that up to 60% of parishioners, including foreign students, migrants and Tatars themselves, do not understand the Tatar language.
Imams fear that their sermons in Tatar "will not reach the entire audience."
Yesterday, the plenum of the Tatarstan Duma unanimously decided to hold Friday sermons in the mosques of the republic only in the Tatar language.
As stated by the Mufti of Tatarstan Kamil Samigullin, this should be an incentive for young Tatars to "learn their native language."
"For those who say that it is 'hard', in every big mosque we intend to organize Tatar language lessons absolutely free of charge," Mr. Samigullin promised.
He added that "the decision has already entered into force" and today in all mosques sermons "should already be in the Tatar language."
He recalled that the Duma of Tatarstan publishes the magazine "Shura" with typical sermons in the Tatar language.
An imam who does not speak Tatar well enough "can thoroughly prepare for them."
DUM of Tatarstan unites more than a thousand parishes in all municipalities of the republic.
According to the mufti, in the districts Friday sermons are conducted exclusively in the Tatar language.
At the same time, in Kazan, a number of mosques previously used mainly the Russian language.
In particular, as the mufti pointed out, this was practiced in the Burnayev mosque, Zakabannaya and Eniler.
However, Mr. Mukhametshin emphasized, the management sets the task that all students speak both state languages of the republic, regardless of nationality.
"There can be no question of any infringement of The Netatar Muslims," Mr. Mukhametshin stressed, explaining that the sermon itself "is not mandatory, the main part of namaz."
At the same time, namaz itself will continue to be read in Arabic, lectures and lessons in Russian language will be preserved in mosques.
At the same time, Rafik Mukhametshin told Kommersant that there was no serious threat of displacing the Tatar language from mosques.
In addition to Russian and Tatar, other languages, for example, Uzbek or Tajik, according to his information, are not used in sermons in the republic.
The decision of the DUM was actively supported by the executive committee of the World Congress of Tatars (CGT).
The head of the executive committee of the CGT, Rinat Zakirov, told Kommersant: "Mosques are an important part of our national life."
It would be sad if the Tatar language left this sphere.
He noted that preaching only in the Tatar language is "the desire of the imams themselves," but the executive committee of the CGT "considers this correct."
The imams interviewed by Kommersant, who conducted sermons at the Russian, are ready to comply with the decision of the DUM, but believe that parishioners will have difficulties with understanding the clergy.
Both Tatars and Russians go to the mosque.
Many do not understand the language.
They, of course, will be tough.
"We will have to rebuild," said Farhat Mavletdinov, imam of the Burnayev Mosque.
According to him, sermons in Russian language are closer even to many Tatars, since "Russian in schools, kindergartens, on the radio - everywhere initially."
However, he believes that the mosque will be able to continue lessons and lectures in Russian language, which are held on other days.
We rely on Allah.
Allah will show a way out of this situation," he concluded.
But about 60% of our country do not know the Tatar language.
These are Uzbeks, Tajiks and Azerbaijanis.
A lot of foreign students come to us: Africans, Arabs.
"That's why we switched to Russian for four years," the imam says.
He believes that in the Tatar language, sermons will "reach a narrower circle and will not reach the entire audience."
But we will obey the decision of the plenum.
It's just that the outcome of the sermons will be different.
But time will tell.
"For example, it will only be easier for me, because the Tatar language is my native language," Gabdulla Galiullin concluded.
The former director of the Federal Penitentiary Service was put on trial
The Moscow Prosecutor's Office approved the indictment in the criminal case investigated by the ICR GSU on the embezzlement of budget funds allocated for the needs of the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia.
The former head of the prison department Alexander Reimer and his deputy, who caused damage to the Federal Penitentiary Service in the amount of more than 2.7 billion rubles, will appear before the court.
The Metropolitan Prosecutor's Office sent to the Zamoskvoretsky District Court a criminal case against the former director of the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia Alexander Reimer, his former deputy Nikolai Krivolapov, as well as the director of the FSUE "Center for Information and Technical Support and Communications of the Federal Penitentiary Service" (FSUE TSITOS) Viktor Definitov.
Depending on the role and degree of participation in the commission of crimes, they are charged by the GSU of the ICR in Moscow under Part 3 of Article 285 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (abuse of office, entailing serious consequences), Part 4 of Article 159 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (fraud committed using their official position, as part of an organized group, on a particularly large scale).
In addition, Krivolapov is charged under Part 1 of Art. 222 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (illegal acquisition and storage of ammunition).
According to the ICR, in 2010-2012, these persons fraudulently stole from the state treasury budget funds allocated by the Federal Penitentiary Service to provide the department with electronic monitoring systems for controlled persons, the so-called electronic bracelets.
To embezzle budget money, the members of the group developed a scheme according to which the enterprise FSUE CYTOS, with which the relevant state contracts were concluded, controlled by them, produced technical means of control and supervision, including "electronic bracelets", and sold at prices inflated several times.
Despite the fact that FSUE CYTOS did not have production equipment, buildings, structures for the placement of production facilities that allow creating a complete production cycle of "electronic bracelets", five state contracts worth more than 3.3 billion rubles were concluded between it and the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia.
As a result of this scheme, more than 2 billion rubles were on the accounts of the Samara branch of FSUE, of which 1.2 billion rubles were stolen.
According to the investigation, more than 140 million rubles. cashed funds were received personally by Mr. Reimer in his office from one of the accomplices, the criminal case against which was allocated to a separate proceeding.
Nikolai Krivolapov, who participated in the fraud, was found to have cartridges of unknown origin for the award pistol, which made it possible to bring an additional charge against him.
In this case, the volume of which amounted to 133 volumes, the Federal Penitentiary Service filed a lawsuit against the defendants for compensation for material damage in the amount of 2.7 billion rubles.
Footballer Hakan Shukyur is suspected of involvement in the coup.
Turkish authorities issued an arrest warrant for former football player and then member of parliament Hakan Shukur and searched two of his family's homes.
The star of Turkish football of the 1990s - early 2000s, striker Hakan Shukur, is wanted by the country's authorities in connection with the coup attempt that occurred last month.
The forward, who retired in 2008, is accused of belonging to an "armed terrorist group."
We are talking about the movement "Hizmet" - a society associated with the famous Turkish religious figure and oppositionist Fethullah Gulen.
It is president Erdogan who considers the organizer of the attempted military coup that occurred on July 15.
Fethullah Gulen lives in the United States, the Turkish authorities demand his extradition.
According to local media, today an arrest warrant was issued for Hakan Shukyur, the police have already conducted searches in two houses that belong to the family of the former football player.
According to investigators, in addition to Hakan Shukur himself, Fethullah Gulen's organization included his father.
However, neither the former footballer himself nor his relatives were there.
He and his family now reside in the United States.
When he was a footballer, Hakan Shukur defended the colors of several Turkish clubs and played for the national team.
He spent most of his career at Galatasaray.
The list of foreign clubs includes the Italian "Torino", "Inter" and "Palermo", as well as the English "Blackburn".
However, he did not spend more than one season in any of them.
Hakan Şükür is still the most productive striker of the Turkish national team: he has 112 matches for the national team and 51 goals.
In 2013, Hakan Shukur left his deputy post because of the corruption investigation that began around Erdogan's party and his inner circle.
According to the Turkish newspaper Hurriyet, arrest warrants were issued in Turkey on July 25 for at least 42 journalists.
They are accused of facilitating a military coup and links with opposition Islamic preacher Fethullah Gulen, who lives in the United States.
Given the severity of the charges, media workers could face lengthy prison sentences ranging from ten years to several life sentences.
