WSJ: The United States is considering imposing sanctions against Russia because of the hacking of the servers of the Democrats.
US officials are considering the introduction of new sanctions against Russia in response to the hacking of the servers of the Democratic Party, writes The Wall Street Journal, citing sources.
Reportedly, in order to impose sanctions, the administration of US President Barack Obama will have to officially accuse Russia or hackers supported by the Russian authorities of attacking servers.
According to sources, the FBI and other US intelligence agencies are almost certain of Russia's involvement in the cyber attack.
The WSJ notes that usually the United States prefers not to specify by name those who carry out hacker attacks.
The exception is the hacking of the database of Sony Entertainment Pictures in 2014, the responsibility for which was officially assigned to the DPRK.
Last year, however, Obama issued an executive order making it easier to impose sanctions on those who carry out or facilitate cyberattacks.
Initially, it was directed against China, but can be used against other countries.
The process of deciding on sanctions can be lengthy, the newspaper writes.
Even if officials conclude that the hackers were supported by Russia, they will have to weigh the possible consequences before making a decision on disclosure.
They will have to determine whether the incident is serious enough to exacerbate tensions in bilateral relations.
Earlier it was reported that the administration of Barack Obama admits the possibility of applying sanctions against the state, whose hackers broke into the servers of the national committee of the Democratic Party.
The WikiLeaks website published emails from the Democratic National Committee.
The media reported that hackers working with the Russian authorities may be involved in the hacking.
The Kremlin called such reports absurd.
FAS fined Google almost half a billion rubles
The reason was the violation of competition in the mobile application market.
Antimonopoly proceedings were initiated by Yandex.
The Russian company claimed that Google provides smartphone manufacturers with access to Android components on terms that prohibited the pre-installation of applications from other developers, in particular, from Yandex.
Fas found confirmation of these claims and found that the company abused its dominant position in the market and imposed on mobile device manufacturers the installation of other applications along with the Google Play store.
Following the results of the inspection, the Federal Antimonopoly Service decided to punish Google, said the deputy head of the FAS Alexei Dotsenko.
The fine must be paid within 60 days after the entry into force of the resolution.
The FAS concluded that the law on the protection of competition must be complied with by all companies, including transnational corporations.
In turn, Google intends to first study the decision and only then decide on further actions: execute it or challenge it.
The Federal Antimonopoly Service recognized the company as a violator of the competition law in September last year and ordered to adjust the contracts until December 18.
However, Google did not give consent to this.
Since then, the company and the department have been conducting legal proceedings.
The FAS noted that, despite the fine, they are discussing with Google the possibility of concluding a settlement agreement.
This measure will lead to nothing.
This opinion of Ekho Moskvy was expressed by the leading analyst of mobile research group Eldar Murtazin.
Murtazin also noted that the fine will not affect either users or the competitiveness of the corporation.
