Lenses are rough, curvy features of tools that create more than 30 million corrected selfies per day.
Any mistakes quickly become common knowledge.
Snapchat lenses have come under fire in the past when they've been accused of the app touting dark facial skin or encouraging bleached faces as an ideal of beauty.
So when some users were offered a lens this week that gave them oblique eyes, crooked teeth and chubby cheeks, some critics saw it as a racist caricature of "yellow-faced" Asians.
And they wondered if these recurring controversies pointed to the company's bigger problem of diversity.
On Wednesday, reports spread and then outrage in reports on The Verge and Motherboard, a day after Snapchat said it had removed the feature.
The company commented: the lens was intended as a reverence for anime characters, not as a caricature of Asians.
But to experts who know about racism firsthand, the lens reminded them of offensive stereotypes in action.
Others completely rejected the comparison with anime.
In an email, Grace Sparapani, a Korean-American art student whose tweet about the photos was actively shared, said the lens was "offensive and at least embarrassing."
She added that "it's hard to argue with the comparison side by side of a very crude caricature of Asians and the filter effects.
This shows that the filter is not just yellow-faced, but highly derogatory yellow-faced.
Snapchat isn't the only company going through these cultural bridges.
American culture seems embroiled in an endless struggle for diversity and inclusion, ranging from corporate boardrooms to Hollywood and the devices we all carry with us.
And the huge audience of young people on Snapchat — who are more racially diverse than their older generation — could mean they're more likely to be educated.
When one of Snapchat's lenses creates an image that is offensive to the user, then, 25-year-old Katie Zhu said in an interview Thursday, "it's much harder for this course of events to go unnoticed as it used to be."
On Thursday, Zhu, a product manager and engineer who works for Medium, decided to delete her Snapchat account and urged others to do the same.
In an article for Medium and in a phone interview, she said she believes racial tensions are the reason for the lack of diversity in recruitment in Snapchat.
Zhu criticized the company's predominantly white, male-only management and ended her article with the hashtag: #DeleteSnapchat.
As Zhu, who herself is a Chinese-American, wrote, "Either they didn't have enough non-white people on their staff to make such decisions, or they have non-white people working for them, but they don't hold positions in which to speak out safely and openly."
Other reviewers share her point, complaining that Snapchat did not answer most of her questions.
The company does not publish information on the representation of national minorities in its state, emphasizing its status as a private company.
On Thursday, Snapchat declined to discuss the racial background of its staff, but according to a confidant, the company recently hired a recruiter to focus on underrepresented segments of the population and active attempts to engage internal resources.
For her part, Zhu said she would keep her Snapchat account private, adding, "I wonder if they really need more users like us so they can say it won't go that way."
Military leadership distorts intelligence on ISIS, congressional commission says
Officials at U.S. Central Command have altered intelligence reports to present a more optimistic picture of the war against Islamic State in Iraq and Syria than events on the ground suggest, a congressional panel said in a report released Thursday.
An interim report from a task force set up by the Republican chairmen of the House Armed Services Committee, the Intelligence Committee and the Subcommittee on Military Appropriations found "widespread discontent" among Central Command intelligence analysts who claim leaders have corrected their assessments of U.S. efforts to defeat the Islamic State.
Central Command, known as Centcom, is the main military command in Tampa, Florida, that oversees U.S. military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
"Intelligence documents approved by Centcom's high command tended to give a more optimistic portrayal of U.S. counterterrorism than confirmed by actual data from the field, and were consistently more optimistic than analysis provided by other intelligence agencies," the report said in a news release on the report.
"What happened at Centcom is unacceptable: When an unreliable analysis is presented to senior management, our military suffers," said Rep. Ken Calvert, a Republican from California.
Problems with management in centcom reach the very top of the organization.
The ten-page report details the shortcomings that constantly arose in 2014 and 2015 in the description and analysis of American actions aimed at training the Iraqi armed forces provided by the Central Command.
While he does not provide definitive evidence that members of the Obama administration ordered the reports to be falsified, he argues that analysts felt that Centcom's leadership was forcing them to present a more optimistic view of the threat from the Islamic State, also known as ISIS or ISIL.
"Throughout the first half of 2015, many of the Central Command's press releases, statements, and testimonies to Congress were significantly more optimistic than actual events," the report said.
For example, a Centcom official has publicly stated that a major military attack aimed at recapturing Mosul could begin as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq's second-largest city, remains under Islamic State control.
"After months of investigation, we know this for sure," Rep. Mike Pompeo, a Kansas Republican, said in a statement.
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, the top intelligence leadership of U.S. Central Command forged the command's intelligence documents to downplay the threat posed by ISIS in Iraq.
Republicans set up a task force when they learned analysts had expressed concern that intelligence about the Islamic State had been tampered with.
As the investigation progresses, the report released Thursday will be followed by more detailed data.
An additional, unfinished at the moment, investigation of centcom's intelligence data is being conducted by the chief inspector of the Ministry of Defense.
Representatives of the Democratic Party in the Intelligence Committee of the House of Representatives of the US Congress published on Thursday their own data, which is consistent with some of the conclusions of the Republican task force.
"Between 2014 and 2015, Centcom created an overly closed procedure for making intelligence assessments regarding ISIS and Iraqi security forces," Rep. Adam B. Schiff, D-Calif., the Democratic party's top representative on the committee, said in a statement.
That procedure, Schiff said, "stalled the release of intelligence documents," damaged analysts' morale, and "does not sufficiently reflect divergent views."
But Schiff and Democrats say they have found no evidence that the White House tried to force Centcom analysts to fit their conclusions to a "predetermined or political interpretation."
Preliminary results of the congressional investigation were presented Tuesday by The Daily Beast.
Last August, The New York Times reported on the existence of an investigation by the Pentagon's inspector general, opened after complaints from Centcom analysts.
Lieutenant Commander Patrick Evans, a Pentagon spokesman, said in a statement that the Defense Department would not comment on the congressional report while the inspector general's investigation continues.
But he said that "experts sometimes disagree on the interpretation of complex data, and intelligence agencies and the Ministry of Defense welcome a healthy dialogue on these vital topics related to national security."
The implications of the investigation go beyond the question of whether the U.S.-led bombing campaign in Iraq and Syria is achieving its goal (as more and more Defense Ministry officials are now claiming).
But last year's statements cast doubt on whether President Obama can rely on Central Command to provide truthful assessments of military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya and other crisis points.
Criticism of the Islamic State's intelligence echoes the controversy that took place more than a decade ago, when Centcom intelligence analyst Gregory Hooker wrote a research article claiming that President George Walker Bush's administration, because of the protest of many analysts, supported a small number of troops in Iraq and did not think about what would follow the 2003 invasion.
Hooker also played a key role in the protest sparked by intelligence on the Islamic State.
Last year, officials said, Hooker's team concluded that despite public statements to the contrary, airstrikes on Islamic State-owned refineries had not led to a significant deterioration in the terrorist group's financial situation because it had built temporary refineries to sell oil on the black market.
But the discovery was not disseminated outside of Central Command, the Times reported in September.
The then commander of centcom, General Lloyd J. Austin III, was criticized last year after testifying in the Senate, which many lawmakers saw as an overly optimistic assessment of the war.
General Austin resigned in April and was replaced by Gen. Joseph L. Votel.
