In the midst of the frenzy of the Olympic Games - the "zen" of jumping on a trampoline
Wherever you are, no matter how much time it is, it's the Olympics.
The events in Rio de Janeiro seem unchanging and inevitable, it is a frenzied combination of competition and aspiration.
As if the Olympic flame itself is the burning torch that is transmitted from archer to swimmer, to gymnast, to triathlete.
You can't turn on the TV, read the newspaper, or overhear your neighbors taking turns talking in a coffee shop and not hear about Simone Biles, Katie Ledecki, or the feud between Michael Phelps and Chad de Clos.
And then there's Logan Dooley.
Dooley, who is competing in the Olympics for the first time, handsome with dimples on his cheeks, could well be among those celebrities shown in prime time promoted by sponsors and life-affirming commercials if he were a swimmer, gymnast or even a fencer.
But Dooley, 28, from Lake Forest, California, is vying for gold in an Olympic trampoline competition.
The Olympic flame does not cover all events in the same way.
Further from the center, partially in the shadows, are those sports that are not universally recognized: air pistol shooting, archery, badminton, taekwondo.
Breaststroke will always be with us, a long reign.
But if I'm allowed to timidly speak out in defense of my personal passion, let me draw your attention to the modest charm of jumping on a trampoline.
Although trampoline jumping has been an Olympic sport since 2000, when it debuted at the Sydney Games, it has received so little recognition in the past 16 years that many people I interviewed were unaware that they belonged to Olympic sports at all.
This could be regional ignorance.
Although the United States sent athletes to competitions, they never won a medal in trampoline jumping, and their athletes did not reach the final until 2012.
The Chinese and Russians tend to share men's awards, while the Chinese and Canadians share women's awards.
Dong Dong of China and Rosie McLennan of Canada will defend their London gold medals this year.
But trampoline jumping has the charm of an outsider, in part because, for the unenlightened ear, it is more likely to be associated with a circus college than with the Olympic Games.
Here I must confess that I am not an expert, but only a down-to-earth enthusiast.
They do have comic potential — it's a caricature of never-ending jumps — but also the grace of gymnastics and diving, two sports that they mostly combine.
The word "trampoline" comes from the Spanish word "el trampolín", meaning "springboard for diving".
Contenders for victory jump on a giant trampoline, soaring into the air for almost 30 feet, and must perform a series of acrobatic tricks (turns, folds and flips) before finally landing on their feet.
They are judged on their performance, complexity and "flight time", according to the official program of the Olympic Games.
Thirty-two athletes from 17 countries, 16 men and 16 women, will compete in Rio.
The most common Olympic course is forward.
Medal contenders must go further, faster, higher and higher in pursuit of gold, sometimes to the finish line, and sometimes back and forth, back and forth across the field.
They aspire not only to the finish line or the starting wall, but also, in full view of television cameras, to another teasing milestone: a world or Olympic record.
This stubborn desire is noble, admirable, even fanatical – and it is enough to make even the viewer cry.
But it is also, in my opinion, somewhat tiring when watching the Games.
From it, jumping on a trampoline gives a respite.
The direction of the trampoline is upwards.
Moving forward is not the goal.
He or she jumps up, seems weightless like an astronaut, flies up, then down, then effortlessly up again.
And in them, of course, there is no competition or difficulties, but throughout the program there is no insane zeal for the finish, no long jump, only the wondrous, graceful disappearance of time and gravity.
It is the closest Olympic sport to Zen.
The women's qualifying competitions, followed by the final, will be held on Friday afternoon, broadcasting at one o'clock in the afternoon Eastern European Time; men's - on Saturday, also at one o'clock.
NBC will broadcast the final as part of the afternoon program starting at 2 p.m. on both days.
In the midst of the Olympic madness, a calm, beautiful moment is expected, which can be easily overlooked in a common dump.
And if consciousness growth can only be achieved by exposing male athletes to the coveted gaze and objectification — as male gymnasts from the United States recently suggested, according to the Wall Street Journal — Dooley is just waiting for his new admiring crowd of fans.
"A generation protests" in Ethiopia, a longtime U.S. ally
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Demonstrators demanding political change in Ethiopia have faced fierce opposition from the government.
Eyewitnesses say dozens of protesters were fatally injured during clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia really on the brink of division?
Over the past decade, it has been one of Africa's most stable countries, a firm ally of the West with a booming economy.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have shaken the country, spreading to an increasing number of its territories.
In the past week alone, thousands of people have taken to the streets, demanding radical political change.
According to human rights advocates, the government's response has been brutal.
Eyewitnesses claimed that police officers shot dead dozens of unarmed demonstrators.
Video footage from protest sites, allegedly filmed late last year or early this year, shows security officers beating young men with sticks as they are placed with their hands against a wall.
The top United Nations human rights official is now calling for a thorough investigation.
"It has always been difficult to keep this country from disintegrating, and it will continue to be even harder," said Rashid Abdi, head of the Horn of Africa project at the International Crisis Research Group.
Ethiopia is Africa's second most populous country after Nigeria, and its stability is supported by the West.
U.S. military and intelligence services are working closely with Ethiopians to combat terrorist threats in the region, especially in Somalia, and virtually no country in Africa receives such support from the West.
Ethiopia's economy is growing at an impressive rate.
Its infrastructure has improved significantly – there is even a new commuter train in the capital Addis Ababa.
And its streets are generally quiet, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia was hardly a model of democracy – human rights organizations constantly mention government repression – opposition in the state was suppressed, due to the fact that dissidents were actually silenced.
Many of them were exiled, imprisoned, killed or exiled to remote deserts.
But that could change.
"If people are constantly suppressed and left with no options but to protest, there will be an uprising," said Seyum Teshome, a lecturer at a university in central Ethiopia.
All young people are protesting.
A generation is protesting.
Complaints range from land use to the seizure of power by a government coalition.
After widely criticized elections last year, the government party and its allies have completely ousted the opposition and now control 100 percent of Parliament.
At the same time, tensions along the border with Eritrea are rising; the struggle for this uncertain, disputed border claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups that have been more or less destroyed in recent years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to exploit the unrest and rearm.
A number of factors explain why bitter feelings, which have been simmering in the depths of the soul for several years, are flare up now.
The first, it would seem, is completely harmless: smartphones.
In the last couple of years alone, a large number of Ethiopians have been able to socialize as cheap smartphones have become commonplace and internet service has gotten better.
Even when the government shuts down access to Facebook and Twitter, as is often the case, especially during protests, many people still find a way to communicate through proxy servers that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians said that was how they organized themselves for the protests.
Second, there is more solidarity between the Oromo and Amhara, the two largest Ethiopian ethnic groups.
Oromo and Amhara are not natural allies.
For centuries, the Amharas of Ethiopia's predominantly Christian highlands flourished in politics and business, exploiting the Oromo, many of whom are Muslims and live in low-lying areas.
But that's also changing.
"We will work together under a unified command," said Mulatou Gemechu, oromo's leader.
The largest protests took place in the districts of Amhara and Oromo.
Many of Amhara and Oromo feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, which makes up about 6 percent of the population and which controls military and intelligence services, trade and politics.
The third reason for the unrest is the loss of Meles Zenawi.
Meles, a former rebel leader, served as Ethiopia's acting prime minister for 17 years, until his death from an unknown illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could foresee danger.
Analysts say he was particularly adept at recognizing the first signals of discontent and using scouts to obtain data and neutralize opponents.
"The current regime lacks common sense," said Abdi, a conflict analyst.
Ethiopia's new prime minister, Hailemariam Desalen, appeared out of nowhere and took Meles' place.
Unlike Meles, who was originally from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam is a Southerner.
Analysts say he does not enjoy the trust of the security services controlled by Tigray.
Many fear that this will lead to more bloodshed as a result.
The last time Ethiopia experienced such unrest was in 2005, after thousands of people protested against what analysts said appeared to be an election that the government locked up and then falsified the results.
In the ensuing crackdown, many Protestants were killed, albeit in smaller numbers than in recent months, and this period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts commended Ethiopia's leaders for their visionary infrastructure development, such as a new intercity train and significant successes in the fight against poverty.
But it is clear that this has not stopped the growing internal discontent with the Ethiopian government.
And it takes on a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in Gondar, a city in Amhara, attacked businesses owned by Tigray, and anti-Tigray hatred on social media is becoming pervasive.
Analysts say the protesters are putting the United States and other Western allies in an awkward position.
The U.S. government has used Ethiopia as a base for drone flights over neighboring Somalia, though it recently announced it had closed the base.
On the one hand, it is clear that the West wants to support democracy, but on the other hand, it does not want its ally to lose strength in an already unstable region.
"And it's going to be hard to walk that tightrope," Abdi said.
