Condoms with chili powder and fireworks increase the protection of Tanzanian elephants
Environmentalists in Tanzania are using an unconventional way to prevent elephants from wandering into human settlements by throwing condoms filled with chili powder at them.
The method proved effective, and the Honeyguide Foundation, which came up with the idea a few years ago, together with the U.S. Committee for Conservation, took it upon themselves to promote it, training volunteers in villages in northern Tanzania to use a nonviolent, four-step way to protect their homes and crops without harming animals.
Previously, many used spears to defend themselves.
Friday will be World Elephant Day, dedicated to the protection of animals.
"Since we invented the toolbox ... we have seen a change in attitudes within these communities, making them much more confident that they will be able to keep elephants out of their fields without harming elephants," Honeyguide chief executive Damian Bell said in a statement.
The first two steps consist of lighting a torch in front of an elephant that has violated the border and giving signals with a horn.
If it was not possible to scare him away, then the so-called "chili cloud" is thrown.
Chili powder mixed with soil is placed with a cracker in a condom, and its end is twisted, only the wick remains outside.
When ignited, the condom bursts with a thud, spraying fine dust of chili powder in the air.
One breath is usually enough to turn an elephant in the other direction.
The last resort is a launcher that shoots Roman candles into the air, producing a loud, bright explosion.
