Community legal centers refuse to serve 160,000 people a year
Each year, more than 160,000 of the most vulnerable people are denied service at community legal centers as the sector prepares for the effect of further funding cuts on already stretched activities.
In Queensland, three out of five people — mostly the elderly, immigrants, vulnerable workers, victims of violence, people unable to combat unjust dispossession, and so on — have already been rejected in an attempt to get free legal aid and representation.
Community legal services, already operating beyond their capabilities, are preparing for further cuts.
From June next year, these legal centers should lose another 30 percent of federal funding.
James Farrell, director of the Queensland Community Legal Centres, said that according to the latest census report of the National Association of Community Legal Centres, thousands of people a year are already being rejected.
Farrell said that if the federal government's decision is not reversed, the situation will only get worse.
"Queensland's community legal centres are consistently underfunded, meaning that thousands of people are denied the vital services they need," he said.
People leaving abusive relationships, people with unmanageable and ruinous debts, families going through divorce, unfairly laid off workers — all of these people have legal problems, and this report shows that they can't get the help they need.
The federal government will cut funding by 30 per cent from June 2017, meaning thousands of less protected Queensland residents will be forced to deal with complex legal issues without assistance.
We call on Justice Minister and Queensland Senator George Brandis to immediately reverse these funding cuts so that people can get the help they need when they face legal challenges.
Last year, the state government fulfilled its commitment to raise funding for free legal aid to the national average.
Now it is time to pay attention to the needs of community legal centers and communities, their clients, and it is time for the Palaschuk government to invest in this important work.
Donald Trump's campaign headquarters sued after an employee allegedly threatened with a gun
According to reports from New York, Donald Trump's campaign headquarters have been sued: allegedly, the headquarters did nothing after the report that its coo in North Carolina threatened an employee with a gun when they were driving in a jeep in February.
The incident was described in a lawsuit filed Wednesday in state court in Charlotte by Vincent Bordini, a former software instructor at the state campaign.
Bordini said he waited months for the problem to be resolved internally, but realised "it's not going to happen".
Director Earl Phillip "pulled out the gun, put his right index finger on the trigger and pointed the muzzle at Vincent's kneecap," Bordini said in the complaint.
After complaining to the local and regional office of the campaign headquarters, Bordini realized that at least four other people had become participants in similar incidents with Phillip, the appeal claims.
"Guns don't have to shoot to cause damage," Bordini said in the complaint.
The lawsuit comes just two days after the Republican presidential nominee made a splash by telling listeners in North Carolina that "Second Amendment people" — understood as gun owners and gun enthusiasts — could act if his rival Hillary Clinton was elected and able to elect judges.
The Trump campaign said the media took his words out of context and that he had not spoken out in support of violence.
In his complaint, Bordini demands compensation from the campaign headquarters for negligent control, and from Phillip for threatening physical violence, insulting by action and causing moral harm.
Trump spokesman Hope Hicks is slow to respond to a request for comment.
Attempts to talk to Phillip were unsuccessful.
WCCB, a local news partner in Charlotte, reported that Phillip recently left the campaign headquarters.
In response to a call to his consulting firm, Innovative Consulting Services, no one quickly called back.
Republican presidential candidate Donald Trump ran a controversial campaign.
Case: Bordini v. Donald J. Trump For President Inc., 16-CS-14300, General Court, Division of the High Court for the District of Mecklenburg, Charlotte.
