Adblock Plus, Facebook play cat and mouse on ad blocking
For companies that make money from online advertising, trying to circumvent ad-blocking software is a game of cat and mouse, according to one of the companies that makes such software.
On Thursday, just a couple of days after Facebook announced it was going to block ad blockers on its desktop version of the site, Adblock Plus published a blog post saying that users can update their filters in the program to block ads on the social network again.
On Tuesday, Facebook announced that the desktop version of the site will change the layout around its ads to make it harder for ad blockers to recognize which parts of a page are ads.
But Adblock now claims to have been able to bypass the new code.
In a blog post, Adblock spokesman Ben Williams wrote that "this kind of mutual struggle between the open source ad blocker community and those trying to circumvent it has been going on since the invention of ad blocking," and it's possible that Facebook will introduce its own solution soon.
The fact that the world's largest social network has entered the fray is a clear sign of just how big a problem ad blockers have become for the industry.
Globally, about 200 million people use ad blockers, according to last year's study by Pagefair and Adobe; almost four times the number of those who used such software in 2013.
With 1.3 billion daily active users who access Facebook via mobile devices, mobile advertising now accounts for 84 percent of Facebook's advertising revenue.
However, the company is hunting for ad blockers on the desktop version, as mobile ad blockers are ineffective in Facebook's mobile apps for the social network and Instagram, according to a spokesperson.
But still, advertising in the desktop version is a sufficiently profitable item for Facebook to consider such a step a profitable investment.
Also on Thursday, Facebook announced that it is going to update its "advertising preferences" tool to give people more control over how ads are targeted.
On Thursday, Facebook said the new Adblock filters were causing concern, as they would also block some non-promotional content on the site.
"This is not going to be a positive experience for people and we plan to address this issue," a Facebook spokesperson said in an official email.
Ad blockers are a rough tool, so we've instead focused on creating tools like Ad Preferences to put control in people's hands.
A woman was moved on a Swiss motorway in an episode of apparent suicide
The victim was lying on the freeway in the middle of the night.
Police are calling witnesses after the woman ran over several vehicles on the freeway early Thursday morning in an apparent suicide attempt.
The incident occurred on the A1 near The Walrus in the canton of Vaud just after midnight on Thursday.
The woman lay down on the road in the dark "in a gesture of desperation" and was hit by several vehicles, Police said in a statement.
Apparently trying to kill herself, the victim, a Swiss woman aged 49, was hit by several vehicles, including a truck.
She died on the spot.
Several of the drivers involved have already been interviewed, but some have not yet been identified, police said, urging them and anyone else who witnessed the incident to respond.
A criminal case was opened, a "logical" step in such a situation, lawyer Gilles Hofstetter told Le Tribune de Geneve.
However, it remains to be seen whether any of the drivers involved will be charged.
Was it possible to avoid the impact?
That's what the prosecutor should determine," Hofstetter said.
Two other similar cases over the past five years suggest that drivers will not be found responsible.
In each case — both involving a person walking in the dark on a freeway — a verdict was handed down that motorists could not expect a random encounter with a pedestrian on the freeway in the middle of the night, the newspaper reported.
Last year, an officer was acquitted of causing death by negligence after she struck and killed a man lying on an A1 near Payern on the night of August 2014.
The 22-year-old victim drank and fainted on the road, the court heard.
The court found that the female police officer — who answered the emergency call — was driving the vehicle in a manner that was justified, and that having a person on the road was a "completely exceptional and unpredictable situation," the judge said.
Anyone with information about Thursday's incident near Walrus should call police on 021 644 83 46 or 021 644 44 44.
NASA Climate Model: Venus Was Once Habitable
Venus may have once been habitable, according to estimates from NASA's new climate model.
Scientists at NASA's Goddard Space Research Institute have developed a model to study Venus' past, using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climatologists.
The model was developed to determine whether Venus, with its hot, anhydrous surface and atmosphere supersaturated with carbon dioxide, could ever have had conditions similar to those on Earth.
Scientists have previously assumed that the small rotation rate of Venus is due to its dense atmosphere.
But the latest simulation suggests that Venus could probably have had a rarefied atmosphere similar to Earth's and still rotate slowly.
The model also looked at the topography of early Venus.
The planet likely had more arid regions than Earth, but it once had enough water and enough geographic variability to create the conditions for life and prevent rapid evaporation.
Early Venus also benefited from the sun, which was 30 percent dimmer.
"According to the GISS model, the slow rotation of Venus exposes its dayside to the sun for almost two months at a time," GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio explained in a press release.
This warms the planet's surface and produces rain, which creates a thick layer of clouds that acts like an umbrella protecting the planet's surface from substantially the sun's heat.
The result is average climatic temperatures, which, surprisingly, are a few degrees colder than these days on Earth.
The model shows the history of Venus, similar to the development that was previously assumed by experts in the study of planets.
Even though Venus may have once been habitable, it has been exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet radiation for several billion years.
Its oceans evaporated and its water vapor was scorched by ultraviolet radiation.
When its hydrogen evaporated, all that remained was a dense atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a deadly greenhouse effect — that is, Venus as we know it today.
The researchers shared the results of their new climate model of Venus in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
