Kepler measures the rotational velocities of stars in the Pleiades cluster
The latest mission of the Kepler Space Telescope helped astronomers to collect the most complete catalog of the rotation rates of stars included in the Pleiades cluster.
The new data help astronomers understand why the stars in the cluster rotate at different speeds, as well as how rotation periods correlate with planet formation.
"We hope that by comparing our results with other star clusters, we will learn more about the relationship between the mass of the star, its age and even the history of its solar system," Louise Riball, a researcher at the Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis at the California Institute of Technology, said in a press release.
The Pleiades Cluster is 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster are just reaching maturity; they were born about 125 million years ago.
They're spinning as fast as they'll never be again.
At their peak rotational speeds, these maturing stars eject large amounts of stellar wind.
Traveling through the magnetic fields of stars, these winds have an inhibitory effect on the stars.
As the star ages, its rotation rate begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the rotation rate of each star by tracking the time between the appearance of recognizable starspots, such as sunspots.
The latest catalogue of rotation rates suggests that more massive stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Riball compares stars to dancers: larger pirouettes make pirouettes slower than smaller ones.
"In the 'ballet' of the Pleiades, we observe that those that rotate slowly are usually more massive, whereas those that rotate faster usually belong to very light stars," Riball said.
Because the Pleiades cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory for comparing the properties of stars with rotational velocities.
"The Pleiades star cluster provides a starting point for theoretical models of the rotation of stars, both younger and older," Riball said.
We still want to know a lot about how, where and why stars slow down their rotation and hang up their "dance shoes," figuratively speaking.
Riball and her colleagues have detailed their latest analysis of the Pleiades' rotational velocities in three new papers that will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
