Sandwiched between Angola and South Africa, Namibia suffered greatly during the long struggle against apartheid.
However, since gaining independence from South Africa in 1990, this country of 2.4 million people has made tremendous strides, especially in the last few years.
The main reason for Namibia's success is that the Government pays great attention to education.
While people in developed countries take free primary and secondary education for granted, in many poor countries secondary and even primary schools require tuition fees.
Moreover, governments are often advised to introduce tuition fees for "cost recovery".
In Namibia, however, primary school education is free.
Moreover, since 2015, secondary education has also become free.
The authorities of the country are also actively working in other important areas.
Efforts to eradicate malaria have reduced the number of annual cases by 97% over the past decade.
Contrary to the international trend of rising inequality, it is decreasing in Namibia.
Compared to 1993, the Gini coefficient, a standard measure of income inequality, has dropped by 15 points.
Then, 23 years ago, this figure was one of the highest in the world.
And the poverty rate has fallen from 69% in 1993 to less than 30%.
The number of people living in extreme poverty (by less than $1.90 a day) has also fallen, from nearly 53% to less than 23%.
Namibia also has the highest freedom of expression rating in Africa, according to Reporters Without Borders.
The country is well ahead of the United States and other wealthy states.
In addition, the country has a favorable rating - one of the highest in Africa - in the "Corruption Perceptions Index", which is compiled by human rights activists from Transparency International.
Even now, when commodity prices are falling, Namibia has managed to maintain a high growth rate.
At the same time, the debt-to-GDP ratio is around 25%, which is less than 1/3 of the debt level in the US and most European countries.
Of course, Namibia also has some problems.
The unemployment rate, at least according to traditional valuation methods, is still quite high - almost 28%.
And, like other countries in the region, Namibia has a high incidence of HIV/AIDS - almost 17% of the population is infected.
The World Bank estimates that Namibia is an upper-middle-income country, but the authorities insist that their country is actually a developing country.
Namibia certainly faces some of the difficulties inherent in underdeveloped economies.
The state has to develop a very large and arid country with a small population.
On the territory of the country in the deserts live isolated nomadic tribes of hunter-gatherers, who one way or another must be integrated into modern society, without losing their identity.
Integrating people who a quarter of a century ago were on the periphery of the world economy is not an easy task for any country.
For Namibia, this is even more difficult: like any other country in the world, it faces the effects of climate change.
However, Namibia did not even think to give up, the country is solving the problems it faces.
Almost immediately after independence, the authorities began to create a diversified economy and a cohesive society.
Notably, rival political factions have come together to work for the common good.
Indeed, Namibia provides cheap health care not only to its own citizens, but also to its neighbours.
About 15-20% of visitors to health facilities in northern Namibia are Angolan citizens.
No one in Namibia is talking about building a wall that would separate the country from its poor and corrupt neighbors.
Namibians realized that neighbors are not chosen, and therefore decided not to conflict with them, but to cooperate - to share scarce water resources, take part in regional medical projects, encourage investment and student exchange.
Moreover, the Government of Namibia has rightly judged that rich natural resources can easily become a curse, contributing to the enrichment of the few at the expense of the many.
The authorities understand that revenues from Namibia's natural resources need to be invested in infrastructure and production capacity.
They also realize that it would be irresponsible not to seek to maximize profits from the sale of the country's resources, and review investment laws and mining contracts to make sure this is the case.
Transparency is crucial to this process, which is why the government's strong support for free speech is so important.
As the head of state Hage Geingob noted, the media often say what he does not like.
But after fighting for freedom from apartheid in South Africa, Namibia must protect the freedoms it gains, the president says.
Not all of Namibia's key resources are exhaustible.
Some – such as fishing – are renewable, and the government is making every effort to preserve and strengthen them.
Every year, more than a million foreign tourists visit the country.
Namibia shows that even those countries that begin with serious shortcomings - racism, colonialism, inequality and underdevelopment - can embark on the path to common prosperity.
Its achievement deserves international recognition and emulation.
Many have heard about the "Gold of Varna" - the oldest gold objects created by man (4600 - 4200 BC).
Perhaps this was the most high-profile archaeological sensation of the 1970s: in Bulgaria, during the excavations of the Varna necropolis, a fantastic number of gold artifacts were found - more than three thousand with a total weight of 6 kilograms.
From one grave alone, known as "Grave No. 43", 990 gold objects with a total weight of more than 1.5 kg were recovered.
However, the official status of the oldest gold in the world may soon move to a nondescript-looking bead found by archaeologists in July this year.
And again in Bulgaria - in a prehistoric settlement known as Tell Unacite.
Unlike Varna, a port city, Tell Unazite is located away from the sea, near the village of Yunatse, Pazardzhik district.
The bead is a gold strip rolled into a ring.
Yavor Boyadzhiev, the head of the excavations at Tella Unacite, dated the find to 4600 BC and stated that it is at least 200 years older than the gold of Varna.
The treasures of Varna, we recall, date back to about the same period, 4600 - 4200 BC.
Technologies that allow you to date metal with impeccable accuracy do not currently exist.
Where is the certainty of which gold is older?
Apparently, Professor Boyadzhiev knows more than he told Reuters: "I am quite sure that Unazite's gold is older than Varna's gold."
This is a find of extreme importance: it looks like a tiny object, but it is large enough to take its rightful place in history.
In an interview with Reuters, Boyadzhiev said that in the near future scientists will analyze the composition of the metal, as well as re-and more carefully study the archaeological layer where the gold artifact was found.
This will help to date the bead as accurately as possible.
The place of discovery also explains a lot.
Tell Unazite is a famous settlement, even if you have never heard of it.
Currently, Tell Unazite is considered the oldest "city" in Europe.
Tell was founded by the descendants of people who migrated to Europe from Anatolia (modern Turkey) in the 7th millennium BC.
Over the following centuries, metal processing developed rapidly in this region, from the development of the first metallurgical skills to the creation of a full-fledged industry.
In Russian historiography, there is a special name for this archaeological community: the Balkan-Carpathian Metallurgical Province.
In the 5th millennium BC, urban-type settlements began to arise around the centers of metalworking.
Now they are called the oldest cities in Europe.
Of these, Tell Unazite is perhaps the oldest, as artifacts from 4900 BC have been found here.
I would call Tell Unazite the prototype of the modern city, although it is a very ancient settlement, even compared to Mesopotamia.
"This place is a thousand years older than Sumer," Boyadzhiev says, referring to the conventional wisdom that urban culture originated in southern Mesopotamia — modern-day Iraq.
There arose the first cities in the usual sense of the word.
Excavations of Tell Unazite have been conducted since 1976.
During this time, archaeologists excavated almost 12 hectares, which is about a third of the estimated total area of the settlement.
The remains of the fortress wall, which once reached three meters in height, were found.
Little has been preserved of the houses and workshops, but archaeologists clearly distinguish between streets, public buildings, dense urban development, a "business center" and residential outskirts.
Tell Unazite is often called the "Bird City": dozens of clay figurines of birds have been found here.
All birds are depicted in a state of rest, hence the assumption that they were not decorative objects, but the object of a local cult.
The "bird city" was destroyed around 4100 BC – possibly by Indo-European tribes coming from the northeast.
The nomads had no cities, but there were horses and weapons.
The three-meter fortress walls did not stop them.
Archaeologists have found obvious signs of a brutal massacre: inside the houses were found the remains of old people, women and children with traces of wounds inflicted by battle axes.
New finds and new facts appear annually, changing the usual ideas about the ancient history of mankind.
Bulgarian archaeologists are increasingly talking not about individual cultures, but about the "lost" first civilization of Europe, which originated in the Balkans.
A powerful incentive in the search for this civilization was the "gold of Varna", found relatively recently, in 1972.
It is logical that the golden luxury of Varna should have been preceded by something - something like a tiny gold bead created in Tella Unazite.
